04960nam a22007935i 9780823252206DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232522067 a10.1515/97808232522062doi  a(DE-B1597)555265  a(OCoLC)844362711  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL1050002bisacsh04a200.822231 aFletcher, Jeannine Hill, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMotherhood as Metaphor :bEngendering Interreligious Dialogue /cJeannine Hill Fletcher. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aBordering Religions: Concepts, Conflicts, and Conversations00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction: We Feed Them Milk -- tPart I. In Mission and Motherhood -- t1. Encounter in the Mission Fields -- t2. We Meet in Multiplicity -- tPart II. In the Sacred Secular -- t3. Encounter in Global Feminist Movements -- t4. Creativity Under Constraint -- tPart III. In Lives Intertwined -- t5. Encounter in Philadelphia -- t6. The Dynamic Self as Knower -- tConclusion: Seeking Salvation -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWho is my neighbor? As our world has increasingly become a single place, this question posed in the gospel story is heard as an interreligious inquiry. Yet studies of encounter across religious lines have largely been framed as the meeting of male leaders. What difference does it make when women’s voices and experiences are the primary data for thinking about interfaith engagement?Motherhood as Metaphor draws on three historical encounters between women of different faiths: first, the archives of the Maryknoll Sisters working in China before World War II; second, the experiences of women in the feminist movement around the globe; and third, a contemporary interfaith dialogue group in Philadelphia. These sites provide fresh ways of thinking about our being human in the relational, dynamic messiness of our sacred, human lives.Each part features a chapter detailing the historical, archival, and ethnographic evidence of women’s experience in interfaith contact through letters, diaries, speeches, and interviews of women in interfaith settings. A subsequent chapter considers the theological import of these experiences, placing them in conversation with modern theological anthropology, feminist theory, and theology. Women’s experience of motherhood provides a guiding thread through the theological reflections recorded here. This investigation thus offers not only a comparative theology based on believers’ experience rather than on texts alone but also new ways of conceptualizing our being human. The result is an interreligious theology, rooted in the Christian story but also learning across religious lines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aTheological anthropology. 0aWomen and religion. 0aWomenxReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / Sexuality & Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aFeminism.  aInterfaith.  aInterreligious Dialogue.  aMissions.  aMotherhood.  aReligions.  aReligious Diversity.  aTheological Anthropology.  aTheology.  aWomen's Movement.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823252206zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823252206423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823252206/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBA